				<name type="primary" sortindex="1" value="Pentactic" />
			
						                           
						               													<description>Pentactic is a game in the line of FITS or Ubongo, but with more player interaction, where players try to place all their pentominoes on their boards while dropping stones on the opponents&amp;rsquo; boards to prevent them from doing the same.  The board features three different, overlapping playfields, in order to increase replay value:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     8&amp;times;8&amp;#10;     9&amp;times;7&amp;#10;     11&amp;times;6&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;A pentomino is a piece composed of five congruent squares, connected along their edges. There are 12 different pentominoes. Pentominoes are well known in the board game community and lots of games use them.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;N&amp;eacute;stor designed the first version of Pentactic (basic gameplay) back in 1980, while playing with a home-made set of pentominoes. 30 years later, he fine-tuned it and added the 'duel' and 'multiplayer' options.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There are 4 types of gameplay:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Solo play (1 player): You&amp;rsquo;ll need 1 PENTACTIC set.&amp;#10;     Basic play (2 players): You&amp;rsquo;ll need 1 PENTACTIC set.&amp;#10;     Duel (2 players): You&amp;rsquo;ll need 2 PENTACTIC sets.&amp;#10;     Multiplayer (3-6 players): You&amp;rsquo;ll need as many PENTACTIC sets as players.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;It is recommended to use different colored sets in &amp;lsquo;Duel&amp;rsquo; and &amp;lsquo;Multiplayer&amp;rsquo; modes if possible. PENTACTIC sets are available in different colors.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
